initial_story: having the potential for high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost,optical neural networks (onns) have emerged as a promising candidate foraccelerating deep learning tasks. in conventional onns, light amplitudes aremodulated at the input and detected at the output. however, the light phasesare still ignored in conventional structures, although they can also carryinformation for computing. to address this issue, in this paper, we propose aframework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating inputimage data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. the input andoutput parts of the onns are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude andphase information. moreover, mutual learning across different onn structures isintroduced to maintain the accuracy. experimental results demonstrate that theproposed framework significantly reduces the areas of onns with the accuracywithin an acceptable range. for instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33%accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (fcnn) and 74.88% area isreduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.
stories: In the realm of optical neural networks (ONNs), where light is harnessed to perform computations, a new framework called oplixnet is proposed to compress the areas of ONNs while preserving accuracy. By modulating input image data into both the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals, oplixnet expands the potential of ONNs by making full use of all available information. Moreover, mutual learning across different ONN structures is introduced to maintain accuracy. Experimental results showcase significant reductions in areas of ONNs without compromising accuracy. For instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (FCNN) and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.

In the world of optical neural networks (ONNs), where light is utilized to perform computations, a new framework known as oplixnet is proposed to compress the areas of ONNs while preserving accuracy. By modulating input image data into both the amplitude and phase components of light signals, oplixnet unlocks the potential of ONNs by fully leveraging all accessible information. Additionally, mutual learning across various ONN structures is incorporated to maintain accuracy. Experimental results demonstrate significant reductions in the areas of ONNs without sacrificing accuracy. For instance, 75.03% area reduction is observed with a 0.33% accuracy decrease in fully connected neural network (FCNN) and 74.88% area reduction with a 2.38% accuracy decrease in ResNet-32.

Optical neural networks (ONNs) are a type of neural network that utilize light to perform computations. A new framework called oplixnet has been proposed to compress the areas of ONNs while maintaining accuracy. oplixnet modulates input image data into both the amplitude and phase components of light signals, which allows it to fully utilize all available information. Additionally, mutual learning across various ONN structures is incorporated to maintain accuracy. Experimental results show that the areas of ONNs can be significantly reduced without sacrificing accuracy. For example, in a fully connected neural network (FCNN), a 75.03% reduction in area was achieved with a 0.33% decrease in accuracy. Similarly, in ResNet-32, a 74.88% reduction in area was achieved with a 2.38% decrease in accuracy.
